US Consumer complaints analysis

Introduction

This dataset was part of a project on US consumer complaints to finanaical intistituions the brief given was to look at the dataset, porcess it for anlysis and and use multiple types of analysis methods to find patterns in the data and show insights in the current trends in this field.

Dataset and Cleaning

The dataset is composed of data on complaints to financial comapnies with issues regarding financial products

There are:

  • 939 companies
  • 148 unique issues with many more sub issues categories
  • 17 unique products with many more sub product categories

Since the data frame contains mostly nominal data we will need to transform cetain variables using interger and one-hot encoding to prepare the data for machined learning techniques.

Since there are many Issues and Companies factor analysis might be needed to reduce the numbers of levels in these two factors

Analysis

Closed with monetary relief analysis

Are some products more likely to be “Closed with monetary relief” than others?

Looking at the below plot card and bank account products have the highest count of complaints unsurprising as they would have one of the largest user bases.

#Group by monetary relief
                              Monetary_relief <-  Complaints %>% select(1:9,-6,-7,15) %>% 
                                                  filter(Complaints$`Company response to consumer` == 'Closed with monetary relief')
                      
                              Response_by_prod    <- Monetary_relief$Product  %>% fct_count(sort = T,)  %>% top_n(5)
                              Response_by_state   <- Monetary_relief$State    %>% fct_count(sort = T,)  %>% top_n(5) 
                              Response_by_company <- Monetary_relief$Company  %>% fct_count(sort = T,)  %>% top_n(5)
                      
                              Monetary_relief <- bind_cols(Response_by_company[1:5,],Response_by_state[1:5,],Response_by_prod[1:5,])
                              Monetary_relief %<>%  rename(Company = f, 
                                                          State=f1,
                                                          Product=f2,
                                                          )
                              #rm dendundent varibales from global env
                              #rm(Response_by_company,Response_by_prod,Response_by_state)
                      
                              p1 <- Monetary_relief %>%  ggplot(aes(x= Company,y=n))+ 
                                  geom_col(fill = "#03396c") + coord_flip() +
                                  labs(title = 'Number of closed with monetary relief complaints by Company',
                                      subtitle = 'Top 6 Companies')
                      
                              p2 <- Monetary_relief %>%  ggplot(aes(x=State,y=n1)) + 
                                  geom_col(fill = "#03396c") + coord_flip() +
                                  labs(title = 'Number of closed with monetary relief complaints by State',
                                      subtitle = 'Top 6 States') 
                      
                              p3 <- Monetary_relief %>%  ggplot(aes(x=Product,y= n2, ))+
                                  geom_col(fill = "#03396c") + coord_flip() +
                                  labs(title = 'Number of closed with monetary relief complaints by Product',
                                      subtitle = 'Top 6 Products') 
                                  
                      
                              grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, nrow=3)

By Company Stats

Equifax, Transunion holdings annd Experian all have much higher companints than the others. They are conusmer credit reporters tracking everyone credit scores. The Equifax Wikipedia page has a whole section for “Lawsuits and fines” that show all three have been in multiple scandals in 2000, 2013, 2014, 2017 and 2019.

The next four are the biggest banks in america

Unsurprisingly the main insight to be seen is that the bigger the customer base of the comapny the more complaints it accumulates

A “per capita” type measuerment of complaints that weights each company by how large there customer base would give a better esitmate of how poorly the companies customer experience is

By state

Here we can see the more populous state have the most complaints. To alleviate this we can use population proportions to weight each state and then get a number of complaints per capita variable.

Using html.tab() we can extract data from the wikipedia page for US states and parse the information we need.

In the second chart we can see that the NA tag is used the vast majority of the time and is probably not used often in the complaints process perhaps because the users who are logging the complaints do not see value in the tags or the tags are not descriptive or intuative enough

From all three charts we can see that the proportions of product, company response and tags remain consistent across state indicating that the system of financial institutions operates on a national level not a regional or local state level.

#Plot the data
                              Complaints %>%  ggplot(aes(fct_infreq(State), fill=Product)) + geom_bar() +     coord_flip() + xlab("States") + theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.direction = "vertical")+ labs(title = 'Number of Complaints by State and Product') -> p1
                      
                              Complaints %>%  ggplot(aes(fct_infreq(State), fill=Tags)) + geom_bar() + coord_flip() + xlab('') + theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.direction = "vertical")+ labs(title = 'Number of Complaints by State and Tag') -> p2
                      
                              Complaints %>%  ggplot(aes(fct_infreq(State), fill=`Company response to consumer`)) + geom_bar() + coord_flip() + xlab('') + theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.direction = "vertical") + labs(title = 'Number of Complaints by State and Company Response')-> p3
                      
                              grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, nrow=1)

HTML tab and per capita weighting

Using HTMLtab package, x-paths and wikiepedia we can downloand the population statistics for each state in the US and use that to weight the complaint conut per state to get a per capita measurement

Also a proportional analysis of the complaint conut per state vs. population proportions by state may be appropriate

# Create url object
                              States_wiki <- "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_states_and_territories_of_the_United_States_by_population"
                      
                              # Xpath file gooten from inpsect html
                              State_pop <- htmltab(States_wiki, which ="//*[@id='mw-content-text']/div/table[1]")
                      
                              #Format the data frame
                              State_pop <- State_pop[1:50,c(3,4,12)]
                              #Turn percentages into decimal float
                              State_pop[,3] <- as.numeric(sub("%","",State_pop[,3]))/100
                              #Turn pop number into a decimal percetange
                              State_pop[,2] <- as.numeric(gsub(",", "", State_pop[,2]))
                              #Add Complaints buy State counts
                              State_Complaints <-  group_by(Complaints,State) %>% 
                                                  summarise(n=n()) %>% arrange(desc(n)) %>% na.omit()
                      
                              #Column state was manually abbreviated and exported
                              #write.csv(State_pop,'State_pop.csv')
                              State_pop_m <- read_csv("State_pop.csv")
                              State_pop[,1] <- State_pop_m[,2]
                      
                              #Test if Complaints states and staes from wikipeadia match
                              State_pop$State %<>% as.factor()
                              testA <- levels(State_pop$State)
                              testB <- levels(Complaints$State)
                              #Missing 7 tiny regions including micronesia other wise fine
                              rm(testA,testB)
                      
                              #Format for left join
                              State_pop$State <- as.character(State_pop$State)
                              Complaints$State <- as.character(Complaints$State)

Here we created a table of states with population and complaints statistics

#Left join and create new column
                              State_Complaints <- left_join(State_pop,State_Complaints)
                      
                              State_Complaints %<>%  mutate(N_Complaints_per_million_citizens = 
                                                              (n / `Census population >> Estimate, July 1, 2019`)*1000000)
                      
                              State_Complaints[,5] <- round(State_Complaints[,5],digits=2)
                      
                              State_Complaints %<>% arrange(desc(N_Complaints_per_million_citizens))
                      
                              #Display table
                              kable(head(State_Complaints)) %>% 
                                  kable_styling(c("responsive","bordered"), font_size = 10) %>% 
                                  scroll_box(width = "100%")
